Probably the worst of them all is the Ring doorbell.

images.alt:
Speaking of a reindeer taking down grandma, a Ring doorbell might be able to capture that kind of footage so you have proof of what happened. But like with the smart speaker, there’s so much more that comes with that purchase. Amazon — and other companies pushing camera doorbells — want you to think they’re making you safer by giving you insight into what’s happening around your home. Ring doorbell ads often also try to make them appear fun, with people putting on a show for the doorbell. But that’s little more than a public relations campaign.

For me, the camera doorbell is the perfect example of a technology that makes people believe they’re safer when really making them more paranoid and anxious as they see their neighborhood and community with deep and unwarranted suspicion. People become aware of things that had already been happening around their home for ages without them knowing about it and they become like big brother, spying out everything once the camera detects movement. It gets even worse when this paranoia meets social media, whether through snitching apps like Nextdoor or the spread of clips on platforms like Facebook that convince others to fear their surroundings and vastly overestimate the amount of crime happening in their vicinity.

record.text: Making some boomer memes for my presentation about GitHub Copilot

images.alt:
his specific meme is about using AI (like large language models such as Gemini or GitHub Copilot) to generate code and the importance of providing sufficient context.

Panel 1 (Anakin): "I'M GOING TO USE AI TO GENERATE CODE"

The Idea: The programmer is going to rely on an AI to write their program code. This is the risky action.

Panel 2 (Padmé): "YOU'RE GOING TO PROVIDE CONTEXT WITH THE PROMPT, RIGHT?"

The Hope: The assumption is that the programmer will give the AI detailed information (context) about the goal, the existing code, the required language, libraries, and constraints—everything needed for the AI to produce good, relevant code.

Panel 3 (Anakin): (Staring)

The Reality: The programmer confirms they will not provide the necessary context. They plan to use a minimal or vague prompt, leading to low-quality or incorrect code.

Panel 4 (Padmé): "YOU'RE GOING TO PROVIDE CONTEXT WITH THE PROMPT, RIGHT?"

The Fear: This expresses the anxiety of experienced developers knowing that without proper context (prompt engineering), AI-generated code often requires far more time to fix and integrate than it saves, essentially creating more work.

In summary, the meme pokes fun at the common developer mistake of using AI to generate code without providing enough context in the prompt, leading to poor results.

external.description: **Abstract:** This paper proposes a novel approach to mitigate quantum decoherence in large-scale superconducting qubit networks leveraging adaptive entanglement swapping. This approach minimizes the impact of environmental noise and enhances the fidelity of quantum operations, paving the way for realizing fault-tolerant quantum computation.
